Over the past two decades, terror management theory (TMT) 
researchers have accrued extensive evidence demonstrating 
how individuals respond to the problem of the threat of death 
(Rosenblatt, Greenberg, Solomon, Pyszczynski, & Lyon, 
1989). Given the basic premise that death awareness, or mor-
tality salience, can be paralyzing, TMT posits that humans 
have evolved psychological strategies—such as self-esteem 
(Pyszczynski, Greenberg, Solomon, Arndt, & Schimel, 
2004)—as defenses against the existential angst that thinking 
about their own mortality elicits. The bulk of TMT research 
has focused on positive self-evaluations as buffers against 
death-related anxiety. Studies indicate that during periods of 
mortality salience, individuals increase their adherence to cul-
tural values and worldviews in order to contribute to or play a 
part in something more enduring than the self (e.g., Gailliot, 
Stillman, Schmeichel, Plant, & Maner, 2008; Maheswaran & 
Agrawal, 2004).
Although terror management processes may be universal in 
the sense that they are designed to help people cope with mor-
tality salience, the specific techniques used to cope should 
nevertheless be culturally contingent. Though this has long 
been acknowledged by TMT theorists (Greenberg et al., 1990), 
few empirical studies have explored the nature and divergence 
of such coping processes across cultures.
The vast majority of TMT studies have focused on Euro-
pean Americans and typically have found that individuals 
employ defensive strategies to protect the self in the face of 
mortality salience (for a review, see Greenberg, Solomon, & 
Pyszczynski, 1997). Such self-protective strategies include 
derogating people who are dissimilar to the self (including 
out-groups) and promoting people who are similar to the self 
(including in-groups; e.g., Rosenblatt et al., 1989), as well as 
psychologically distancing the self from innocent victims 
(Hirschberger, 2006; Hirschberger, Florian, & Mikulincer, 
2005). These strategies involve positively evaluating entities 
that are similar to the self and devaluing those that are differ -
ent. These findings are consistent with long-standing Western 
ideas of the self as an individualistic, independent entity (e.g., 
Markus & Kitayama, 1991). Thus, death is viewed primarily 
as a threat to the self, and efforts to cope with death involve 
restoring the self.
In Eastern cultures, the self is viewed not as an independent 
entity, but as an entity inherently tied to the collective. Hence, 
we posit that mortality salience should have a different effect 
on Asian Americans than on European Americans. Under 
interdependent self-construal (Markus & Kitayama, 1991), the 
East Asian self is one whose feelings, needs, and thoughts are 
tied to those of other people (Chentsova-Dutton & Tsai, 2010). 
Consequently, the threat of death should derive not from the 
