disintegration of the self, but from the disintegration of social 
ties. Thus, among Asian Americans, mortality salience should 
spur efforts to restore or affirm others, rather than the self.
1
We hypothesized that mortality salience should produce 
divergent cultural responses. Given prior research, we pre-
dicted that European Americans would respond to mortality 
salience with self-protective strategies aimed at affirming the 
self and derogating dissimilar others. In contrast, we predicted 
that Asian Americans would respond to mortality salience by 
using strategies aimed at affirming other people and by becom-
ing less derogating of those dissimilar to the self. In the face of 
death, Asian Americans should seek to bolster the connected-
ness between individuals. The importance of the self should 
decrease, whereas the importance of other people should 
increase.
To test this hypothesis, we conducted two studies using dif-
ferent TMT paradigms. In Study 1, we presented European 
Americans and Asian Americans with either a mortality-
salience or a control prime and then measured participants’ 
attitudes toward a person who was dissimilar to themselves—
a prostitute. Past research has shown that in the face of mortal-
ity salience, European Americans tend to derogate dissimilar 
others, as such derogation indirectly bolsters the self by affirm-
ing the validity of one’s cultural worldview (Rosenblatt et al., 
1989). We predicted that whereas European Americans would 
opt for this strategy under mortality-salience conditions, Asian 
Americans would actually embrace the dissimilar other to 
affirm their interdependence and to bolster the collective.
At first glance, it is counterintuitive that embracing a non-
normative individual would be a form of promoting the collec-
tive. Traditionally, Asians’ collectivism applies primarily to 
in-group members (Markus & Kitayama, 1991), and prosti-
tutes stand, at best, as “fringe” in-group members and, at 
worst, as out-group members. Nevertheless, we believe that 
the use of this kind of dissimilar other is a particularly strin-
gent test of our hypothesis. Given that death threat tends to 
magnify—and often distort—culturally bound attitudinal and 
behavioral patterns, our hypothesis is not so extraordinary.
For example, under normal (i.e., no threat) conditions, 
European Americans tend to endorse egalitarian values and 
are relatively socially liberal (e.g., Chia, Moore, Lam, & 
Chuang, 1994; Ross, 1997; Wang, 1998). However, under 
mortality-salience conditions, European Americans become 
highly nationalistic and derogating of dissimilar others, exhib-
iting a distorted magnification of the general Western tendency 
to enhance the self and all things related to the self. In contrast, 
under normal conditions, Asian Americans tend to be rela-
tively socially conservative. However, we expected that under 
mortality-salience conditions, they would magnify the general 
Asian tendency toward collectivism and interdependence to 
the point of embracing nonnormative individuals, who would 
typically be derogated under no-threat conditions.
In Study 2, we again presented European Americans and 
Asian Americans with the mortality-salience or control prime; 
we subsequently measured their psychological distancing 
from an innocent victim. Existing research shows that blaming 
innocent victims for their plight establishes a sense of psycho-
logical distance from them (Hirschberger, 2006; Hirschberger 
et al., 2005). Thus, assignment of blame is a form of self- 
protection against death threat, as it denies one’s own vulnera-
bility; such protection is functionally achieved when one rejects 
a severely injured victim (Goldenberg, Pyszczynski, Greenberg, 
& Solomon, 2000; Greenberg, Arndt, Simon, Pyszczynski, & 
Solomon, 2000). We predicted that whereas European Ameri-
cans would respond to mortality salience with increased psy-
chological distancing (i.e., to protect the self), Asian Americans 
would respond with decreased psychological distancing (i.e., to 
affirm the interdependence between individuals).
Study 1
Participants
Twenty-two European Americans (7 men and 15 women; 
average age = 20.50 years) and 20 Asian Americans (8 men 
and 12 women of Chinese, Japanese, or Korean descent; aver-
age age = 22.09 years) participated in this study. Of the 20 
Asian Americans, 10 were first generation (i.e., born abroad); 
the remainder were second generation (i.e., born in the United 
States to parents born abroad).
Measures and procedure
Following the typical TMT paradigm, we asked participants to 
write down their thoughts regarding either their own death 
(mortality-salience condition) or dental pain (control condi-
tion). Next, using the procedures described by Cox et al. 
(2009), participants completed the Positive and Negative 
Affect Schedule (PANAS; Watson, Clark, & Tellegen, 1988), 
which served as a delay task (see Pyszczynski, Greenberg, & 
Solomon, 1999).
After completing the PANAS, participants were presented 
with a fabricated legal brief (modeled after the materials used 
by Rosenblatt et al., 1989) concerning a prostitute under arrest 
and awaiting bail. The case brief included the criminal charge; 
the defendant’s address, employment record, length of resi-
dency, and criminal record (i.e., a prostitution conviction 6 
months earlier, no failures to appear in court); a note about the 
defendant’s lack of established community ties; and a recom-
mendation against releasing the defendant on her own recog-
nizance. A copy of the citation that was ostensibly issued to  
the defendant was also included and contained basic arrest 
information.
After reading the materials, participants recorded the amount 
of bail they would assign the defendant. Given that most college 
students are relatively unfamiliar with the bond-setting process, 
we included a statement indicating that most bonds for similar 
offenses ranged from $0 to $999. In addition, participants com-
pleted the Prostitution Attitudes Scale (PAS; Rosenblatt et al., 
1989), which consists of five items concerning prostitution (two 
Culturally Divergent Responses to Mortality Salience 1021
against prostitution and three favoring prostitution); ratings are
 
made on Likert scales ranging from −3 (strongly disagree) to +3 
(strongly agree). The two antiprostitution items were reverse-
coded, and ratings for the five items were averaged to yield an 
overall prostitution attitude score, with higher scores reflecting 
more favorable attitudes toward prostitution. The scale showed 
acceptable internal consistency (α = .74).
Results
A multivariate analysis of variance (ANOV A) showed no main 
effect of gender and no interaction between gender and ethnic-
ity on either PAS score or bail amount (both ps > .86). There-
fore, gender is not discussed here.
The main analyses were 2 (condition: mortality salience vs. 
control) × 2 (ethnicity: European American vs. Asian Ameri-
can) multivariate ANOV As on our dependent variables of 
interest: PAS score and amount of bail. Although the multi-
variate main effect of ethnicity on both measures was marginal 
(Wilks’s λ = .85), F(2, 37) = 3.13, p = .055, the multivariate 
interaction between condition and ethnicity was significant 
(Wilks’s λ = .77), F(2, 37) = 5.31, p = .009. Univariate ANO-
V As performed on each dependent measure separately yielded 
a main effect of ethnicity. Asian Americans reported more 
negative attitudes toward prostitution (M = −0.25, SD = 0.23) 
than European Americans reported (M = 0.46, SD = 0.22), F(1, 
38) = 5.02, p = .031. Asian Americans also posted marginally 
higher bail (M = $549.85, SD = $65.83) than European Ameri-
cans did (M = $385.67, SD = $63.51), F(1, 38) = 3.30, p = 
.077. Ethnicity and condition had a significant interactive 
effect on PAS score, F(1, 38) = 10.263, p = .003 (see Fig. 1), 
and a marginally significant interactive effect on bail amount, 
F(1, 38) = 3.036, p = .090. Planned comparisons showed 
results consistent with existing TMT research: European 
Americans reported a significantly more negative attitude 
toward prostitution in the mortality-salience condition (M = 
−0.0092, SD = 0.28) than in the control condition (M = 1.022, 
SD = 0.34), t(20)= 2.10, p = .048, whereas Asian Americans 
showed the opposite effect (mortality-salience condition: M = 
0.21, SD = 0.31; control condition: M = −0.73, SD = 0.34), 
t(18) = 2.73, p = .013). European Americans posted margin-
ally higher bail in the mortality-salience condition (M = 
$488.46, SD = 81.24) than in the control condition (M = 
$278.88, SD = 81.24), t(20) = 1.89, p = .072. Asian Americans 
showed the reverse pattern (mortality-salience condition: M = 
$495.27, SD = 88.32; control condition: M = $604.44, SD = 
97.64), but this effect was not significant, t(18) < 1, p = .472.
Additional planned comparisons revealed that European 
Americans and Asian Americans differed on PAS score in the 
control condition (mean difference = 1.75), t(16) = 5.17, p < 
.001, but not in the mortality-salience condition (mean differ -
ence = 0.22), t(22) < 1, p = .53. Likewise, European Ameri-
cans differed from Asian Americans on the bail posted in the 
control condition (mean difference = $325.65), t(16) = 2.70, 
p = .015, but not in the mortality-salience condition (mean dif-
ference = $6.81), t(22) < 1, p = .95.
To address the possibility that mood drove the observed 
effects, we calculated net positive-mood scores using the 
PANAS (i.e., by subtracting the ratings given to the negative-
mood items from the ratings given to the positive-mood items). 
Analyses of PAS scores and bail amounts revealed no main 
effects of mood or interactions involving mood (all Fs <1).
Discussion
Study 1 provided evidence that mortality salience causes cul-
turally divergent responses, such that European Americans 
become more negative in their attitudes toward individuals 
who violate their worldviews, whereas Asian Americans 
become less negative in their attitudes toward such individu-
als. It is important to note that European Americans and Asian 
Americans in the control condition had disparate attitudes 
toward prostitutes (i.e., European Americans were more sym-
pathetic toward prostitutes than were Asian Americans), so 
that the divergent pattern of responses of the two cultural 
groups actually led the groups to converge in their attitudes in 
the mortality-salience condition. This finding highlights the 
methodological importance of establishing baseline attitudes 
when comparing cultural groups.
We acknowledge that Study 1 had certain limitations. First, 
the nature of the dependent variables introduced a possible 
confound with political ideology. Given that Greenberg, 
Simon, Pyszczynski, Solomon, and Chatel (1992) found that 
liberals exhibited the same trend as the Asian Americans did in 
our study (i.e., they responded to mortality salience with 
increased tolerance), and that conservatives exhibited the 
same trend as the European Americans (i.e., they responded to 
mortality salience with decreased tolerance), it is possible that 
the observed cultural effects simply reflected a difference in 
political conservatism across cultures. However, given that 
