Asians tend to be more, not less, conservative than European 
Americans (Chia et al., 1994; Ross, 1997; Wang, 1998), this 
confound is unlikely.
Second, Study 1 was limited insofar as it measured 
responses to a highly nonnormative other person. However, 
past ethnographic research has demonstrated instances in 
which Asians have extended their collectivism to nonnorma-
tive individuals within their culture. Cultural anthropologists 
have argued, for example, that prostitutes are not necessarily 
condemned in traditional Chinese culture, given that a large 
number of rural women choose this type of work to support 
their family members (Robbins, 2008, p. 188). Likewise, 
many contemporary Japanese women view selling their bodies 
for sex, at least in certain contexts, as no different from other 
part-time jobs and as an acceptable form of capitalism  
(Moffett, 1995). In other words, although prostitution may be 
nonnormative insofar as it is not generally prescribed as a 
favorable manner of making one’s living, it may nevertheless 
be tolerated under certain conditions (i.e., when other eco-
nomic opportunities are lacking).
Furthermore, embracing nonnormative individuals can also 
serve to bolster the collective for Asian Americans insofar as it 
offers a way of integrating previously excluded members into 
the group, thereby expanding the in-group. Given that for  
the interdependent self, mortality salience poses a threat to the 
collective and the sustainability of social ties, bolstering the 
in-group through the integration of fringe members may alle-
viate the threat. Nevertheless, to answer the question of 
whether the same pattern would emerge with more normative 
targets, we conducted Study 2.
Study 2
Participants
Forty-eight European Americans (23 men and 25 women; 
mean age = 18.7 years) and 23 Asian Americans (11 men  
and 12 women of Chinese, Japanese, or Korean descent; mean 
age = 18.4 years) participated in Study 2. Of the 23 Asian 
Americans, 4 were first generation; the remaining participants 
were second generation.
Measures and procedure
Participants completed the same manipulation used in Study 1, 
then the PANAS as a delay task, and finally an attribution task 
modeled after the one used by Hirschberger (2006). For the 
attribution task, they were handed a fabricated local-news arti-
cle describing a serious car accident that left a university 
employee, “Steve,” facing possible paralysis. The article made 
it clear that the employee was following all traffic rules and 
that the accident was not his fault. Participants were then given 
the Assignment of Blame Scale (ABS; Hirschberger, 2006), a 
four-item scale assessing their reaction to and attribution for 
the cause of the victim’s state. Sample items include, “Steve is 
to blame for his condition” and “Steve could have done more 
to avoid his situation.” Participants rated their agreement with 
each item on a scale from 1 (strong disagreement) to 7 (strong 
agreement). The scale exhibited acceptable internal consis-
tency (α = .62).
Results
There was no main effect of gender on ABS score, nor were 
there any significant interactions involving gender (all Fs < 1). 
Thus, gender is not discussed further.
A univariate ANOV A on the effects of ethnicity and condi-
tion on ABS score revealed a main effect of ethnicity, F(1, 68) = 
7.13, p = .009. Asian Americans assigned higher blame to the 
victim (M = 2.01, SD = 0.16) than European Americans did 
(M = 1.50, SD = 0.13). However, this main effect was qualified 
by a significant interaction between ethnicity and condition, 
F(1, 68) = 11.05, p = .001 (see Fig. 2). Planned contrasts 
revealed results consistent with existing TMT research: Euro-
pean Americans in the mortality-salience condition blamed the 
victim more (M = 1.68, SD = 0.14) than did those in the con-
trol condition (M = 1.31, SD = 0.15), t(46) = 2.119, p = .040. 
However, Asian Americans in the mortality-salience condition 
blamed the victim less (M = 1.55, SD = 0.29) than did those in 
the control condition (M = 2.48, SD = 0.19), t(22) = 2.15, p = 
.043. Additional planned contrasts revealed that ABS scores 
differed significantly between European Americans and Asian 
Americans in the control condition (mean difference = 1.16), 
t(34) = 4.65, p < .001, but not in the mortality-salience condi-
tion (mean difference = 0.13), t(33) < 1, p = .68.
To once again address the alternative explanation that mood 
drove the observed effects, we calculated net positive-mood 
