Discussion
Results from Study 2 provide further evidence that the pattern 
of responses of Asian Americans and European Americans 
diverged. European Americans blamed the victim more in the 
mortality-salience condition than in the no-threat (control) con-
dition (presumably because they used blame to psychologically 
distance themselves from the victim), whereas Asian Americans 
blamed the victim less in the mortality-salience condition than 
in the no-threat condition. Rather than psychologically distanc-
ing themselves from the innocent victim, Asian Americans 
demonstrated increased psychological closeness to the victim 
after thinking death-related thoughts. Again, these divergent 
responses ultimately led the two groups to appear similar under 
mortality-salience conditions. Given that European Americans 
and Asian Americans in the control condition had different reac-
tions to the victim, mortality salience caused cultural conver -
gence by leading European Americans to increase their blame 
assignment and Asian Americans to lower their blame assign-
ment; thus, the two groups differed in the control condition, but 
not in the mortality-salience condition.
General Discussion
In these studies, death threat (i.e., mortality salience) caused 
cultural divergence in response patterns, but led to cultural 
convergence in actual attitudes. This cross-cultural similarity 
in outcome belies the divergent underlying processes: Death-
related thoughts caused European Americans to defensively 
bolster the self (via derogation of dissimilar others) but caused 
Asian Americans to bolster other people. In Study 1, mortality 
salience produced increased derogation of a culturally nonnor-
mative individual among European Americans, but decreased 
derogation of that individual among Asian Americans. Like-
wise, in Study 2, mortality salience led European Americans 
to blame an innocent victim more, but led Asian Americans to 
blame him less.
2
One potential limitation of this work is the use of Asian 
Americans rather than Asians born and raised in Asia. Given 
past work demonstrating that bicultural individuals can acti-
vate different (cultural) selves in different situations (e.g., 
Greenberg et al., 1992), one alternative explanation for our 
findings is that mortality salience activated the more culturally 
dominant self (i.e., the Western self) among the Asian Ameri-
cans. We offer two arguments against this possibility. First, 
many cultural-psychology studies have relied on bicultural 
individuals; past studies that have compared European Ameri-
cans with both Asian Americans and Asians from Asia have 
typically found the latter two groups to be highly culturally 
similar to each other and culturally dissimilar to European 
Americans (e.g., Chentsova-Dutton & Tsai, 2010; Iyengar & 
Lepper, 1999; Kim & Sherman, 2007; Taylor et al., 2004; 
Taylor, Welch, Kim, & Sherman, 2007). Second, our findings 
showed that Asian Americans and European Americans 
responded to mortality salience in divergent ways, thereby 
casting strong doubt on the possibility that a Western self was 
activated for the bicultural individuals.
In sum, this research demonstrates both the universality of 
the terror management system—a system evolved to help 
humans cope with the awareness of their own mortality—and 
its cultural contingency. On the one hand, death is a universal 
problem—one that leads individuals to increase their adherence 
to their culturally prescribed worldviews. On the other hand, 
death-related thoughts produce very different responses among 
members of different cultures—though as our findings show, 
such disparities may appear to indicate cross-cultural similarity. 
It is important to note, however, that our findings of divergent 
processes are consistent with TMT’s basic premise: When death 
is salient, people affirm the self. Although the manifestation of 
such self-striving is different across cultures (given differences 
between individualists’ and collectivists’ views of the nature of 
the self), the underlying goal is nevertheless the same.
Going beyond terror management, this work sheds light on 
the fact that although different processes may often be at work 
in different cultures, they may produce ironically similar 
results—a phenomenon that, up to this point, has received lit-
tle attention in cultural psychology. Future work should more 
closely explore how, and when, different processes lead to 
similar outcomes among different cultural groups.
Declaration of Conflicting Interests
The authors declared that they had no conflicts of interest with 
respect to their authorship or the publication of this article.
Notes
1. Although interdependence/independence is only one aspect of 
culture, it is particularly relevant to 
TMT given that this dimension 
fundamentally concerns the self. At the core of TMT is the question 
of how individuals protect the self in the face of existential terror; 
cultural differences in how the self is construed should be particularly 
meaningful in this context.
2.
 It is important to note that in both studies, evaluations of the tar -
get did not implicate any evaluations of the in-group. 
The targets, 
though dissimilar to the participants (e.g., as a nonnormative other in 
Study 1 and an innocent victim facing paralysis in Study 2), were not 
directly oppositional to either cultural group’s worldviews. Whether 
Asian Americans would demonstrate the same pattern under different 
conditions (e.g., in the presence of a target critical of their in-group) 
is a question for future research.
